{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:13:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:13:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19728"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19728"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.71,0.19,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12506"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88263"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12506"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72453"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2287"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29991"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44441"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88263"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for routine antenatal care at 30 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy which has been uncomplicated. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. She received influenza and pertussis vaccines two weeks ago. She enquires about the respiratory syncytial virus (RSV) vaccine after hearing about it from her antenatal class.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate recommendation regarding RSV vaccination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vaccination is contraindicated due to recent influenza and pertussis vaccination","Vaccination is recommended now","Vaccination should be deferred until after delivery","Vaccination should be deferred until winter","Vaccination is only recommended if there are pregnancy complications"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case addresses the recommendations for RSV vaccination in pregnancy. The RSV vaccine (Abrysvo) is funded on the National Immunisation Program for pregnant women between 28-36 weeks gestation. The aim is to provide passive immunity to protect newborn infants from severe RSV disease in their first months of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination is recommended now\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option. At 30 weeks gestation, she falls within the recommended window of 28-36 weeks when maternal antibody transfer to the fetus is optimal. The vaccine is both recommended and funded during this period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination should be deferred until after delivery\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The purpose of vaccination during pregnancy is to provide passive immunity to the infant through maternal antibody transfer. Vaccination after delivery would not achieve this goal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination is contraindicated due to recent influenza and pertussis vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. RSV vaccine can be safely co-administered with other recommended pregnancy vaccines, including influenza and pertussis vaccines, with no waiting period required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination should be deferred until winter\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While RSV disease is more common in winter, the timing of vaccination is based on gestational age rather than season to ensure optimal antibody transfer to the fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaccination is only recommended if there are pregnancy complications\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The vaccine is recommended for all pregnant women between 28-36 weeks gestation, regardless of pregnancy complications or risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["RSV vaccine (Abrysvo) is recommended and funded on the National Immunisation Program for pregnant women between 28-36 weeks gestation.","RSV vaccination during pregnancy provides passive immunity to protect newborn infants from severe RSV disease.","RSV vaccine can be co-administered with other recommended pregnancy vaccines including pertussis and influenza."],"references":["Australian Immunisation Handbook. Australian Government: Department of Health and Aged Care. Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccine-preventable-diseases/respiratory-syncytial-virus-rsv#recommendations","Pregnant women are recommended to receive an RSV vaccine during pregnancy to protect the infant [Internet]. The Australian Immunisation Handbook. 2025. Available at: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/recommendations/pregnant-women-are-recommended-to-receive-an-rsv-vaccine-during-pregnancy-to-protect-the-infant","\u200cRoyal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Pre-pregnancy and pregnancy-related vaccinations [Internet]. Melbourne: Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists; 2020. Available at: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Pre-Pregnancy-and-Pregnancy-Related-Vaccinations.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72453"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19728"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72453","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/72453"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-02T19:43:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-02T19:44:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12506"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88263"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":